Compute alpha-diversity

Here, we compute the alpha-diversity via the alpha() and pd() function from the microbiome and picante package, respectively.

# We'll use species-level feature table for estimating alpha-diversity
physeq_s <- tax_glom(physeq, "Species")

# Compute Observed features, Peilou's Evenness and Shannon index
adiv_npd <- alpha(physeq_s, index = c("observed", "evenness_pielou", "diversity_shannon")) %>%
  rownames_to_column("SampleID")

# Compute Faith's Phylogenetic Diversity
adiv_pd <- pd(samp = t(otu_table(physeq_s)), tree = phy_tree(physeq), include.root = F) %>%
  select(PD) %>%
  rownames_to_column("SampleID")

# Putting together
adiv <- inner_join(adiv_npd, adiv_pd, by = "SampleID") %>%
  inner_join(rownames_to_column(metadata, "SampleID"), by = "SampleID") %>%
  rename("Observed species" = observed, "Pielou's Evenness" = evenness_pielou, 
         Shannon = diversity_shannon, "Faith's PD" = PD) %>%
  gather("adiv", "value", "Observed species":"Faith's PD") %>%
  mutate(FishID = as.character(FishID), NetPen = as.character(NetPen), 
         adiv = factor(adiv, levels = c("Observed species", "Pielou's Evenness", "Shannon", "Faith's PD")))

Plot alpha-diversity

p <- ggplot(adiv, aes(x = SampleType, y = value)) +
  geom_boxplot(aes(fill = SampleType), outlier.shape = NA) +
  geom_jitter(shape = 16, position = position_jitter(0.2)) +
  facet_wrap(~adiv, nrow = 1, scales = "free_y") +

Alpha-diversity group significance

Fit linear mixed effects models

The alpha-diversity plot showed different dispersions among the sample type. Hence, well log transform the response variables to stabilize the mean-variance relationship

# Split the dataframe by alpha-diversity indices
adiv_spl <- split(adiv, f = adiv$adiv)

# Fit model
lme <- lapply(adiv_spl, function(x) 
              lmer(log(value + 1) ~ Diet * SampleOrigin + (1|FishID) + (1|NetPen), data = x)) 
## boundary (singular) fit: see ?isSingular
## boundary (singular) fit: see ?isSingular

From the model outputs, we can see that the standard deviation of random effect NetPen for Observed species and Pielous Evenness is zero, which indicates boundary fits. Well update these models by removing NetPen from the models.

lme <- lapply(lme, function(x) 
              if(is.null(x@optinfo$conv$lme4$messages)) {
                x
              } else {
                update(x, . ~ . -(1|NetPen))}
              )

The updated models are not singular after removing the random effect NetPen. We proceed to model diagnostics.

Model diagnostics

Here we use the ggResidpanel package to produce a panel of plots for residual diagnostics.

lapply(
  seq_along(lme), 
  function(x) 
  {
    # Extract titles 
    main <- ggdraw() + draw_label(names(lme)[x], fontface='bold')
    # Make residual diagnostic plots
    resid_panel <- resid_panel(lme[[x]], plots = "all", qqbands = T)
    # Assemble plots
    plot_grid(main, resid_panel, ncol = 1, rel_heights = c(1, 10))
  }
)

Inference

For the significance testing of fixed effects, the likelihood ratio test (LRT) is often used. However, it can produce anti-conservative p values in situations where the data is unbalanced or the number of parameters is large compared to the number of observations. A better alternative is to use F test with Satterthwaite/Kenward-Roger approximation available from the lmerTest package.

fixef <- lapply(lme, function(x) anova(x, ddf = "Kenward-Roger"))
fixef

Conditional contrasts

When interactions between main factors are included in the model, marginal means averaged over the levels of other covariates in the model can be misleading. A good practice is to specify conditional contrasts through the use of the simple argument to contrast().

# Compute estimated marginal means for factor combinations
emm <- lapply(lme, function(x) emmeans(x, ~ Diet * SampleOrigin))

# Conditional contrasts 
ccomp <- lapply(emm, function(x) 
                contrast(x, method = "consec", simple = "each", combine = TRUE, adjust = "mvt") %>%
                summary())
ccomp

Display effects

Gather p values

# Gather p values of main effects
p_fixef <- lapply(fixef, function(x) rownames_to_column(x, "term")) %>%
  bind_rows(.id = "adiv") %>%
  rename(p_val = "Pr(>F)") %>%
  mutate(p_val = formatC(p_val, format = "f", digits = 3),
         p_val = paste0("p = ", p_val),
         p_val = gsub("p = 0.000", "p < 0.001", p_val),
         term = gsub("Diet:SampleOrigin", "Interaction", term),
         term = gsub("SampleOrigin", "Sample origin", term),
         label = paste0(term, ": ", p_val))
  
# Gather p values of conditional contrasts
p_ccomp <- bind_rows(ccomp, .id = "adiv") 

# Make a dataframe for conditional p value annotation   
anno1 <- filter(p_ccomp, SampleOrigin != ".") %>%
  mutate(SampleOrigin = gsub("Contents", "DIC", SampleOrigin),
         SampleOrigin = gsub("Mucosa", "DIM", SampleOrigin)) %>%
  separate(contrast, sep = " - ", c("start", "end")) %>%
  mutate(start = paste0(start, "-", SampleOrigin),
         end = paste0(end, "-", SampleOrigin))
  
anno2 <- filter(p_ccomp, Diet != ".") %>%
  mutate(contrast = gsub("Contents", "DIC", contrast),
         contrast = gsub("Mucosa", "DIM", contrast)) %>%
  # the "end" comes before "start" because we need to use "REF-DIC" as the starting point
  separate(contrast, sep = " - ", c("end", "start")) %>%
  mutate(start = paste0(Diet, "-", start),
         end = paste0(Diet, "-", end)) 
  
anno <- bind_rows(anno1, anno2) %>%
  select(adiv, start, end, p.value) %>%
  # the columns are arranged in a way that p value annotation starts from left to right
  arrange(match(adiv, c("Observed species", "Pielou's Evenness", "Shannon", "Faith's PD")),
          match(start, c("REF-DIC", "REF-DIM", "IM-DIC")),
          match(end, c("REF-DIM", "IM-DIC"))) %>%
  # the following 4 lines of code convert p values to the corresponding asterisks
  mutate(p.value = ifelse(p.value < 0.001, "***", p.value),
         p.value = ifelse(p.value >= 0.001 & p.value < 0.01, "**", p.value),
         p.value = ifelse(p.value >= 0.01 & p.value < 0.05, "*", p.value),
         p.value = ifelse(p.value >= 0.05, "NS", p.value),
         # position of p value label on y axis 
         y = c(180, 195, 210, 225, 0.88, 0.96, 1.04, 1.12, 3.5, 3.8, 4.1, 4.4, 22.5, 24.5, 26.5, 28.5),
         # ensure alpha-diversity indices are plotted in the desired order
         adiv = factor(adiv, levels = c("Observed species", "Pielou's Evenness", "Shannon", "Faith's PD")))

Annotate the plot

# Make a list of alpha-diversity plots
p_list <- lapply(
  as.list(levels(adiv$adiv)),
  function(x) 
  {
    # Make an inital plot
    p <- filter(adiv, adiv == x) %>%
      ggplot(aes(x = SampleType, y = value)) +
      geom_boxplot(aes(fill = SampleType), outlier.shape = NA) +
      geom_jitter(shape = 16, position = position_jitter(0.2)) +
      facet_wrap(~adiv, nrow = 1, scales = "free_y") +
      scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, NA), expand = expand_scale(mult = c(0, 0.15))) +  
      labs(x = "") +
      theme_cowplot() +
      scale_fill_manual(values = brewer.pal(n = 12, name = "Paired")[c(1,2,7,8)]) +
      theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1),legend.position = "none") 
    
    # Add p values of conditional contrasts to the plot
    p <- p + geom_signif(data = filter(anno, adiv == x), 
                         aes(xmin = start, xmax = end, annotations = p.value, y_position = y),
                         map_signif_level = TRUE,
                         tip_length = 0.01,
                         textsize = 4, 
                         manual = T)
    
    # Convert the table containing p values of main effects to a grid graphic
    tg <- filter(p_fixef, adiv == x) %>%
      select(label) %>%
      # the following 2 lines of code remove rownames and column names
      as.matrix() %>%
      unname() %>%
      tableGrob(theme = ttheme_minimal(core = list(fg_params = list(hjust = 0, x = 0.1)),
                                       rowhead = list(fg_params = list(hjust = 0, x = 0))))
    
    # Assemble plots
    lab <- plot_grid(tg, NULL, labels = "", ncol = 1, rel_heights = c(1,2.5))
    plot_grid(p, lab, labels = "", ncol = 2, rel_widths = c(2,1))
  }
)

# Get figure legend
legend <- get_legend(p)

# Assemble plots
prow <- plot_grid(plotlist = p_list, nrow = 2, align = 'v', axis = "l", labels = "")

# Add legend to the assembled plot
plot_grid(prow, legend, rel_widths = c(8, 1))

# Export figure
ggsave(here("result", "figures", "Figure 4.tiff"), width = 10, height = 10,
       units = "in", dpi = 300, compression = "lzw")
